Diagnostic remarks.
This cryptically grey-brown katydid can be recognized by the cuticle of the legs and thorax covered with dense dark dots (
Fig. 24J
), flattened femora with broad lobes on their ventral margins, and aposematically colored, yellow- and black-banded abdomen (

Fig. 
24I

). From 

Cymatomer denticollis

it differs in the lack of two distinct lobes on the dorsal edge of mesothoracic femora (
Fig. 24G
), distinctly more curved ovipositor, and the abdominal sterna without the aposematic red coloration (
Fig. 24H
).
